## Step 5 — ThoughtSpot Formula Examples

```
Business days between a date column and today (exclusive):
  sql_int_op ("{target_db}.{target_schema}.get_business_days_clamped({0},{1}, FALSE)", [date column], today())

Weekday elapsed time as HH:MM:
  sql_string_op ("{target_db}.{target_schema}.get_business_duration_str({0},{1})", [date column], today())

Weekday-only minutes:
  sql_int_op ("{target_db}.{target_schema}.get_business_minutes_clamped({0},{1})", [start], [end])
```

To add a formula in ThoughtSpot via the UI:
1. Open the Model → Edit → + Add formula
2. Paste the expression with your column names and give it a name
3. Save — this creates the formula definition and the visible column entry together

> **If adding via TML:** both a `formulas[]` entry AND a matching `columns[]` entry
> with `formula_id` are required. Without the `columns[]` entry the formula is hidden.
>
> ```yaml
> formulas:
> - id: "formula_Business Days Open"
>   name: "Business Days Open"
>   expr: >-
>     sql_int_op ("{target_db}.{target_schema}.get_business_days_clamped({0},{1}, FALSE)", [{date_column}], today())
>   properties:
>     column_type: MEASURE
>
> columns:
> - name: "Business Days Open"
>   formula_id: "formula_Business Days Open"   # must match id above exactly
>   properties:
>     column_type: MEASURE
>     aggregation: SUM
>     index_type: DONT_INDEX
> ```
>
> For `get_business_duration_str`: use `sql_string_op`, `column_type: ATTRIBUTE`, omit `aggregation`.

> Note: editing TML directly requires the `ts` CLI (Claude Code only). In Cursor,
> use the ThoughtSpot UI or run `/ts-object-answer-promote` in a Claude Code session.

